WEBVTT

00:00:00.001 --> 00:00:04.680
Have you ever wondered what a developer advocate, sometimes called a developer evangelist, does?

00:00:04.680 --> 00:00:09.380
You know the folks. They're often seen at conferences, working at some high-end tech

00:00:09.380 --> 00:00:13.620
company's booth, or traveling from conference to conference speaking on their specialty.

00:00:13.620 --> 00:00:18.460
Who are these folks? How did they get this job, and what is it really like to do it from day to

00:00:18.460 --> 00:00:23.600
day? Join me, along with Cecil Phillip from Microsoft, Matt McKay from Twilio, and Paul

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:28.560
Everett from JetBrains to dig into what it means to be a developer advocate and how they each became

00:00:28.560 --> 00:00:35.880
one for such cool tech companies. This is Talk Python To Me, episode 189, recorded November 28th, 2018.

00:00:35.880 --> 00:00:54.420
Welcome to Talk Python To Me, a weekly podcast on Python, the language, the libraries, the ecosystem,

00:00:54.420 --> 00:00:59.100
and the personalities. This is your host, Michael Kennedy. Follow me on Twitter, where I'm at,

00:00:59.100 --> 00:01:04.420
mkennedy. Keep up with the show and listen to past episodes at talkpython.fm, and follow the show on

00:01:04.420 --> 00:01:08.320
Twitter via at Talk Python. Cecil, Paul, Matt, welcome to Talk Python.

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:09.020
Thanks for having us.

00:01:09.020 --> 00:01:13.020
Yeah, it's great to have you all here. I'm super excited about this, I'm not even sure what we're

00:01:13.020 --> 00:01:19.580
calling it, developer advocate, developer evangelist, developer relations conversation, because I feel

00:01:19.580 --> 00:01:24.480
like this role is a little bit mysterious to many folks in the software engineering field.

00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:30.840
But at the same time, it looks really fun. And I think a lot of folks interact with all of you,

00:01:30.840 --> 00:01:34.340
and it's going to be really fun to just dig into what you do and how you got there.

00:01:34.340 --> 00:01:40.960
So I guess the first place to start will be, where do you work for who you are? A little more background,

00:01:40.960 --> 00:01:45.440
who you are, where you work, and what you do there in terms of this advocacy role.

00:01:46.020 --> 00:01:46.700
Cecil, let's start with you.

00:01:46.700 --> 00:01:52.100
Sure, no problem. So my name is Cecil Fulop. Right now, I'm a developer advocate at Microsoft.

00:01:52.100 --> 00:01:57.480
Primarily, my team focuses a lot on just making sure developers have a really good experience moving their

00:01:57.480 --> 00:02:04.820
applications into the cloud. So as you can imagine, we work a lot with the folks on the Azure side of things,

00:02:04.820 --> 00:02:09.580
but then also, too, we spend a lot of time in the community kind of just going around to various events and doing

00:02:09.580 --> 00:02:11.380
workshops and different things like that.

00:02:11.380 --> 00:02:15.480
All right, excellent. Paul, I'm a developer advocate, using the word advocate.

00:02:15.480 --> 00:02:21.540
We'll get back to that later. JetBrains, primarily for PyCharm, and I'm based out of the U.S.

00:02:21.540 --> 00:02:28.440
I get to tell people I work for a check company founded by Russians out of my basement in Virginia for the Boston office.

00:02:28.660 --> 00:02:41.840
And many of them are in Germany. So yeah, it's quite the international space. And in terms of developer focus, that's basically all you guys do, which is pretty awesome. So you'll have a lot of tools to talk about there. Matt, how about yourself?

00:02:41.940 --> 00:03:04.560
Yeah, so I work in developer relations for Twilio. And I actually been with Twilio for about five years, used to be just an evangelist. Then I was helping to basically serving the evangelism team, leading the evangelism team. And now I run a peer team of the evangelism team, which focuses on helping developers get their code and their stories published on Twilio.com.

00:03:04.560 --> 00:03:06.540
So does that make you like a meta evangelist?

00:03:06.540 --> 00:03:17.620
Well, I still do. I still do a lot of evangelism, but it's more focused on the online activities of getting developers to basically promoting developers who built really cool things with Twilio.

00:03:17.840 --> 00:03:28.040
Yeah. And I guess it's also worth throwing out that other folks may also know some of you from your online stuff. Like Matt, you do full stack Python, which is super popular and well known. That's awesome.

00:03:28.040 --> 00:03:28.440
Thanks.

00:03:28.440 --> 00:03:33.760
Yeah. And Cecil, you're away from the keyboard podcast is excellent as well. People might know you from there.

00:03:33.760 --> 00:03:34.500
Sure. Thank you.

00:03:34.500 --> 00:03:53.080
Yeah, sure. So I guess the first thing is, you know, when you go to college or where you teach yourself programming, there's a big gap between I can now write a program and I'm now representing Azure, JetBrains, Twilio in sort of a public speaking semi marketing thing.

00:03:53.080 --> 00:04:08.180
But you still, you know, I know all three of your programming work and you're all excellent programmers. So there's this deep technical side, but there's also this capability that many people in the software field don't embrace too much like the public speaking and marketing side.

00:04:08.180 --> 00:04:14.640
So the story of how you got there, I think it's really interesting. Maybe we'll go in reverse. Matt, how did you go along that path?

00:04:14.640 --> 00:04:30.980
Yeah. So I I've been programming since I was a kid and then I became full time programmer. I became a tech lead. So I was doing really heads down coding for about eight years. And then I wanted to get out of my own bubble. I live in Washington, D.C. and get out of the tech scene here and kind of explore elsewhere.

00:04:30.980 --> 00:04:53.200
So I did a road trip around the country for five months to 30 different cities and just like send emails to developers and was like, hey, like, what's it like being a software developer in Memphis? Like, what's it like being a software developer? Obviously, San Francisco, Chicago, all places around the country. And then I met a bunch of folks from Twilio. And after I was done with my project, my road trip, they asked me if I was willing to join the company.

00:04:53.200 --> 00:05:05.940
So for me, it was a little bit of getting out of my comfort zone. I still code every single day, but it was sort of stepping out outside of my typical boundaries and then expanding my skill set beyond just programming.

00:05:05.940 --> 00:05:07.620
Man, that sounds like such a cool trip.

00:05:07.620 --> 00:05:12.200
Yeah, you can actually see the pictures. It's codingacrossamerica.com. I still have the website up.

00:05:12.200 --> 00:05:12.640
Really?

00:05:12.640 --> 00:05:15.400
I haven't updated it. Yeah, codingacrossamerica.com.

00:05:15.400 --> 00:05:20.380
Oh, right on. That's awesome. Paul, how about you? Did you do like a world tour or how do you do it?

00:05:20.380 --> 00:05:21.900
No, I sat in my basement.

00:05:21.900 --> 00:05:29.200
But the internet, the traffic, the commute to the basement is way, way nicer. That's for sure.

00:05:29.200 --> 00:05:30.840
Yeah, so tell us about it.

00:05:30.840 --> 00:05:41.440
Sure. I like to joke at Python conferences. I'm not the oldest person you know, but the company that was a Python startup, I was in the Navy in 1994.

00:05:41.440 --> 00:05:45.760
And I wanted a boss. I wanted to be on a team. I wanted to work for something I believe.

00:05:45.760 --> 00:05:48.740
And then I got really lucky to get a job offer from JetBrains.

00:05:49.440 --> 00:05:58.580
And to come back to your lead-in point about what's being asked for, when I was offered the job, my boss, Hadi Hariri, you know really well, Mike.

00:05:58.580 --> 00:06:00.580
Yeah, I've known Hadi for a long time. He's a great guy.

00:06:00.580 --> 00:06:00.980
Fantastic guy.

00:06:00.980 --> 00:06:01.660
Yeah.

00:06:01.660 --> 00:06:01.960
Yeah.

00:06:01.960 --> 00:06:14.060
He said something, and I wonder if Cecil and Matt had the same experience, but he said, it's important for you to be part of the community and be perceived as part of the community.

00:06:14.560 --> 00:06:17.900
And when you do things, you need to do it as you, not us.

00:06:17.900 --> 00:06:22.940
And I thought at the time, that's just BS that you say, but you don't actually believe.

00:06:22.940 --> 00:06:27.200
But I joined the company, and that's actually the way the job works.

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:31.160
You're expected to be respected as a community person first.

00:06:31.160 --> 00:06:38.760
I think that's a great point, and I think it's really interesting that there is this little bit of cult of personality aspect to this job role.

00:06:38.760 --> 00:06:45.740
Like many of the folks that I know in this field, they're semi-well-known, if not really well-known, on their own.

00:06:46.320 --> 00:06:49.360
And I think the companies see that as an advantage.

00:06:49.360 --> 00:06:57.500
Like, we're going to have this person who is really well-known or respected in the community, and their halo will shine off on our company a little bit.

00:06:57.500 --> 00:07:03.840
Indeed, and that's kind of a dark side to that because it implies that we as the company don't have enough reputation.

00:07:03.840 --> 00:07:09.740
We've got to ride the coattails of this person who will then become a mouthpiece for our message.

00:07:09.740 --> 00:07:13.680
And that is thinking backwards along several axes.

00:07:13.680 --> 00:07:14.660
Yeah, sure.

00:07:15.340 --> 00:07:17.240
Cecil, how did you get to where you are?

00:07:17.240 --> 00:07:26.060
You work for a company about 2,500 miles away from where you live, so it's not just down the street either, which I think is a pretty common trait of this role, right?

00:07:26.060 --> 00:07:26.800
Yeah, definitely.

00:07:26.800 --> 00:07:32.220
Most of my teammates, probably not all of them, or everybody's all remote, right?

00:07:32.220 --> 00:07:37.540
So everybody's at some different part of the world, which, as you can imagine, makes meetings a little bit challenging sometimes.

00:07:37.540 --> 00:07:39.980
You get really good with figuring out time zones, right?

00:07:40.860 --> 00:07:46.620
Yeah, exercising, scheduling, calendars for time zones is an exercise in itself.

00:07:46.620 --> 00:07:48.100
That definitely takes a lot of time.

00:07:48.100 --> 00:07:53.660
But for me, I want to say, you know, so I've been in the South Florida community probably ever since I left college.

00:07:53.900 --> 00:08:01.620
And at some point, I decided that, you know, I kind of wanted to reach out a little bit more and get a little bit more than what I was getting inside of the office.

00:08:01.860 --> 00:08:05.940
So, you know, I started to go to user group meetings, and I started to go to these CodeCamp things.

00:08:05.940 --> 00:08:11.960
You know, CodeCamps are like these free technology, kind of like conferences, but not really, like smaller conferences.

00:08:11.960 --> 00:08:17.960
And, you know, I started to go to these things because, you know, I kind of wanted to just be around the community and learn a little bit more than what I was getting.

00:08:17.960 --> 00:08:24.260
And at some point, some person decided, hey, you know, you've got some interesting stuff to talk about.

00:08:24.260 --> 00:08:26.060
Why don't you come up and give a presentation?

00:08:26.060 --> 00:08:28.840
I was like, nah, nobody wants to hear what I have to talk about.

00:08:28.940 --> 00:08:30.760
Like, why in the world would I ever want to do that?

00:08:30.760 --> 00:08:36.260
So after some continuous poking, like eventually I, you know, I accepted it.

00:08:36.260 --> 00:08:37.020
I started speaking.

00:08:37.020 --> 00:08:39.420
And, you know, I just, I got a little bit addicted to it.

00:08:39.420 --> 00:08:42.620
Like, I kept doing it more, and I went to more conferences and whatnot.

00:08:42.620 --> 00:08:45.640
And, you know, that led to a lot of interesting opportunities.

00:08:45.640 --> 00:08:50.220
You know, I became a teacher at Miami Dade College for a little bit.

00:08:50.220 --> 00:08:51.500
I talked there for about three years.

00:08:51.500 --> 00:08:58.040
But, you know, I've always had that, you know, wanting to go out and, you know, talk to people and kind of listen to their problems

00:08:58.040 --> 00:08:59.740
and really just understand what they've been doing.

00:08:59.740 --> 00:09:06.000
And honestly, randomly, one day I saw a message on Twitter and it said, hey, we're building this really cool team at Microsoft.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.260
And I was like, eh, whatever.

00:09:08.260 --> 00:09:09.060
I'm not doing anything.

00:09:09.060 --> 00:09:10.720
I'll just reply to this tweet, right?

00:09:10.720 --> 00:09:12.860
Because, of course, people get tired like that all the time.

00:09:13.680 --> 00:09:18.680
And I got a reply back in a couple interviews later and some formal conversations later.

00:09:18.680 --> 00:09:18.960
Yeah.

00:09:18.960 --> 00:09:19.740
That's awesome.

00:09:19.740 --> 00:09:22.600
You know, that really mirrors my path.

00:09:22.600 --> 00:09:29.060
I mean, I didn't go down the dev relations side of things, but I sort of wanted to branch out from where I was.

00:09:29.140 --> 00:09:31.560
I felt like there wasn't enough growth in what I was doing.

00:09:31.560 --> 00:09:37.700
You know, I felt like, oh, I kind of know at least as much as everyone in the field and the company that I'm working at.

00:09:37.700 --> 00:09:39.760
And how do I how do I get better?

00:09:39.760 --> 00:09:39.980
Right.

00:09:39.980 --> 00:09:42.580
So I started going to user groups and doing speaking.

00:09:42.580 --> 00:09:48.200
And a developmenter actually came to me and said, hey, if you're going to do this for free, we'll pay you to do this if this is the thing you want to do.

00:09:48.200 --> 00:09:50.380
So I said, actually, that's a pretty cool idea.

00:09:50.380 --> 00:09:50.800
I'll do that.

00:09:50.800 --> 00:09:58.000
So, yeah, I think I think it's really interesting how these little steps lead down these paths that you don't necessarily expect.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:05.720
And it also sounds to me like all three of you sort of had that feeling of I'd like to kind of branch out from from where I am for something bigger.

00:10:05.720 --> 00:10:06.680
Right.

00:10:06.680 --> 00:10:11.060
And it kind of led those little steps down that path led to these roles.

00:10:11.060 --> 00:10:11.320
Right.

00:10:11.320 --> 00:10:11.980
Yeah.

00:10:12.020 --> 00:10:18.480
You know, when I spoke to my first manager, he always said, you know, I actually asked him, what do I need to do to prepare for this job?

00:10:18.480 --> 00:10:22.840
And he looked at me and he's like, you've been preparing for this job like all your career.

00:10:22.840 --> 00:10:23.520
Right.

00:10:23.520 --> 00:10:25.000
Which is kind of interesting when you think about it.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:25.160
Right.

00:10:25.160 --> 00:10:33.740
Because as a as somebody that's coming out and just starting into the workforce, you never think, oh, OK, this is what I want to do.

00:10:33.740 --> 00:10:41.940
It's not like your typical career path, I guess, like if you do computer science or if you decide you want to pick up and learn a programming language or web pages or something.

00:10:41.940 --> 00:10:47.320
But so I think it's something that's very like just a part of who you are as a person.

00:10:47.320 --> 00:10:47.560
Right.

00:10:47.560 --> 00:10:48.820
Like, do you like talking to people?

00:10:48.820 --> 00:10:51.060
Do you like, you know, engaging with folks?

00:10:51.060 --> 00:10:53.340
Do you like helping people learn and succeed?

00:10:53.340 --> 00:10:53.700
Right.

00:10:54.100 --> 00:10:58.600
And again, if it's something that you want to do, again, it's just kind of a part of your your DNA as a person.

00:10:58.600 --> 00:10:58.880
Right.

00:10:58.880 --> 00:11:01.160
Like, it's kind of hard to teach those types of things.

00:11:01.160 --> 00:11:01.680
Yes.

00:11:01.680 --> 00:11:09.460
It's funny to me because the side that a lot of people see of evangelists or advocates is speaking on stage or reading a blog post.

00:11:09.460 --> 00:11:16.820
But what it really comes down to for me and what I feel like the best evangelists do, they really just want to help other people, help other developers.

00:11:17.200 --> 00:11:22.500
They retain that sense of curiosity and learning like any programmer, any great programmer.

00:11:22.700 --> 00:11:25.500
But they really want to help other programmers become better.

00:11:25.500 --> 00:11:32.020
And to me, that's like the crux of the job is just like, hey, how do I help other developers at scale?

00:11:32.020 --> 00:11:33.660
That's that's what I get really excited about.

00:11:33.660 --> 00:11:40.200
Yeah, I'll add to both of what I think Matt and Cecil got really to the heart of it, that, yeah, you see the rock star thing.

00:11:40.200 --> 00:11:50.600
But the prime directive is the human side and the deep empathy for people and the desire to measure your success by making other people better.

00:11:50.600 --> 00:11:55.520
That book, Badass, Making Users Awesome, really gets to that point.

00:11:55.520 --> 00:12:00.840
And if you're not wired that way as a human being, then you're not going to be good in this role.

00:12:00.840 --> 00:12:14.520
Would you say that if you're the type of person who really gets a lot of satisfaction of sitting down next to, say, a junior teammate or somebody and like showing them how to start working with an ORM or do something that they haven't done before?

00:12:14.520 --> 00:12:21.240
Does that kind of experience and desire sort of map well to this like more professional version?

00:12:21.240 --> 00:12:21.980
Yeah, definitely.

00:12:21.980 --> 00:12:28.320
And you have to have the humility to say this person I'm sitting next to or this person I'm having a conversation with via email.

00:12:28.560 --> 00:12:31.080
Like they may not know as much in this area.

00:12:31.080 --> 00:12:35.180
And, you know, I'm just going to help them work through the problem as best as possible.

00:12:35.180 --> 00:12:42.860
And just having the humility to – because we've all been – we've all worked with developers who kind of dismiss your questions.

00:12:42.860 --> 00:12:43.940
You can't do that.

00:12:43.940 --> 00:12:49.400
You really have to have empathy for other people and have humility for what your own skills and other people's skills are.

00:12:49.400 --> 00:12:54.940
Yeah, you've got to still feel the pain of learning it, you know, five or ten years ago yourself or maybe not so long ago.

00:12:54.940 --> 00:13:01.680
So I guess one of the things that would be interesting would be sort of talking about what is – what does your job actually look like?

00:13:01.680 --> 00:13:06.560
I mean you have to stay on top of all these technologies, you know, especially you, Cecil.

00:13:06.560 --> 00:13:09.700
Like I feel like Azure has got like a whole new thing every day or something.

00:13:09.700 --> 00:13:11.080
And you're just like, wait, what is this?

00:13:11.080 --> 00:13:13.460
The old thing is new or the new thing is now old.

00:13:13.540 --> 00:13:15.140
This new new thing is the thing.

00:13:15.140 --> 00:13:19.180
So how much of this is like studying, learning, personal research?

00:13:19.180 --> 00:13:20.420
How much is travel?

00:13:20.420 --> 00:13:21.640
How much is public speaking?

00:13:21.640 --> 00:13:23.300
And what else is there to it?

00:13:23.300 --> 00:13:28.240
I want to say in our particular organization, it really depends, right?

00:13:28.240 --> 00:13:33.780
I like to tell people it's kind of like a choose-your-own-adventure type role, at least the way that we kind of approach it.

00:13:33.780 --> 00:13:39.800
So a big part of what we do is, you know, we spend a lot of time with the engineering teams.

00:13:40.160 --> 00:13:47.320
You know, when updates are happening, when new products are coming out, when, you know, tutorials and documentation and like when things are being created, right?

00:13:47.320 --> 00:13:48.340
So we can tell the good story.

00:13:48.340 --> 00:13:54.840
And so a lot of the times, you know, we've been – you'll probably be working with some of these tools or these SDKs before some folks have seen them.

00:13:54.840 --> 00:14:00.340
You know, because, you know, part of the role is, again, it's not just traveling or, you know, being on videos and stuff like that.

00:14:00.340 --> 00:14:02.200
But, you know, we have to provide constructive feedback.

00:14:02.200 --> 00:14:05.560
You know, do people like these things that we're building for you?

00:14:05.560 --> 00:14:07.140
And, you know, is this useful?

00:14:07.140 --> 00:14:09.220
Are we recovering your use cases?

00:14:09.540 --> 00:14:09.900
You know what I mean?

00:14:09.900 --> 00:14:16.880
Like, is this a thing that's going to make it easier for you to build, you know, applications and solutions on top of the platform that we're trying to provide for you?

00:14:16.880 --> 00:14:27.080
And so, you know, what you find is a lot of our teammates, you know, again, other than just, sure, the traveling and all that other stuff, but we try and align ourselves with products that we just generally care about.

00:14:27.580 --> 00:14:33.440
So, you know, like, I spend a lot of time with the Azure Functions team because, you know, I'm really interested in learning about serverless.

00:14:33.440 --> 00:14:38.300
Or, you know, the Service Plus team because, you know, I want to learn about messaging and A or QP, right?

00:14:38.300 --> 00:14:42.160
Because, again, Azure in itself has like 100 and change products, right?

00:14:42.160 --> 00:14:43.700
Maybe even 200 products, right?

00:14:44.160 --> 00:14:49.440
And, you know, each one of them has their own sets of buttons to press and knobs to turn and all that stuff.

00:14:49.440 --> 00:14:52.400
And no one person is going to know all of it or even half of them.

00:14:52.600 --> 00:15:13.100
But, again, like, if you generally care and are passionate about something and you want to see this product succeed or, you know, you want to really understand how this stuff works because your audience that you're focusing on cares about these things, then, you know, you can make the time to sit down and focus on it, read the documentation, create samples about it so you can have like a genuine understanding of, well, this is kind of how this stuff works.

00:15:13.100 --> 00:15:15.060
And here are the pain points are.

00:15:15.060 --> 00:15:16.960
And here's how we can make this better for our communities.

00:15:16.960 --> 00:15:17.980
That's really interesting.

00:15:18.180 --> 00:15:31.740
So it sounds to me like almost you're the first user or consumer of the thing the engineering team is creating in some sense because you're trying to learn it as they're creating it and you're giving them feedback like, whoa, guys, this API is wonky.

00:15:31.740 --> 00:15:33.180
People aren't going to love it.

00:15:33.180 --> 00:15:34.260
Is that accurate?

00:15:34.260 --> 00:15:36.380
Yeah, that happens in most cases, right?

00:15:36.380 --> 00:15:41.340
Most cases, you know, we get to play around with things or see some feedback or slide decks or whatever the case is.

00:15:41.340 --> 00:15:47.060
So we can then, again, make some, you know, make some recommendations or, you know, do some reviews on things.

00:15:47.600 --> 00:15:51.060
Because, again, like, you know, we know our community better than everybody else does, right?

00:15:51.060 --> 00:15:54.200
Because we're out in the field and we're talking to them and we're interacting with them.

00:15:54.200 --> 00:15:56.940
Again, most advocates come from a community, right?

00:15:56.940 --> 00:15:58.700
Like that's, you know, that's kind of how it is.

00:15:58.700 --> 00:16:06.960
And so, you know, with that context, we can look at these products objectively and say, well, you know, I really don't think .NET developers are going to like this thing.

00:16:06.960 --> 00:16:09.260
I really don't think JavaScript folks are going to like that thing.

00:16:09.260 --> 00:16:10.700
Because you know how they work.

00:16:10.700 --> 00:16:11.940
You know what the tool sets are.

