So you can get kind of a wide range of like here.

00:21:53.240 --> 00:21:54.500
And I even have some of my own posts.

00:21:54.500 --> 00:21:57.220
Like, here's how I spend my day as a developer evangelist.

00:21:57.220 --> 00:22:01.020
So that's kind of like one sort of nebulous reason, nebulous area.

00:22:01.020 --> 00:22:02.880
It's like, what tactically does the role look like?

00:22:03.180 --> 00:22:10.400
And then there's the second area, which is like, what's the difference between a developer evangelist, developer advocate, developer relations?

00:22:10.400 --> 00:22:11.940
There's all these titles floating around.

00:22:11.940 --> 00:22:17.060
And to be fair, part of it is actually confusion.

00:22:18.520 --> 00:22:23.180
In a lot of cases, the titles aren't necessarily put out there with a lot of thought behind them by some companies.

00:22:23.180 --> 00:22:29.620
But the way that we view it at Twilio is developer evangelists are called evangelists because they go to where developers are.

00:22:29.620 --> 00:22:35.540
So, for example, like we go to PyCon, the PyCons around the world, because that's where Python developers are.

00:22:35.880 --> 00:22:39.640
And we are showing them how to build Twilio, helping them use Twilio.

00:22:39.640 --> 00:22:47.280
A developer advocate sort of has a different function, which I think the other guys have talked about, which is they're bringing feedback into the company.

00:22:47.280 --> 00:22:52.680
So the evangelists are bringing some feedback in, but I would say it's like 10 to 20 percent of their job.

00:22:52.680 --> 00:22:56.920
Whereas when you're a developer advocate, it's like actually tends to be like 50 percent or more.

00:22:56.920 --> 00:23:05.860
You're bringing feedback in from developers in the community and saying to the product teams like, hey, I think we actually need to change like, you know, the way that this API is structured or something like that.

00:23:06.080 --> 00:23:10.200
And so I think those are kind of like the two large areas that people often have questions.

00:23:10.200 --> 00:23:15.180
And so at least at Twilio, when I joined five years ago, we only had developer evangelists.

00:23:15.180 --> 00:23:23.880
And then from there, we branched out into a developer education team, which works on the docs and what's called Twilio Quest, our training platform, 8-bit adventure training platform.

00:23:23.880 --> 00:23:27.820
We have a developer community team, which sets up events just for Twilio developers.

00:23:28.040 --> 00:23:37.420
And then a team called Developer Voices, which helps to shine the spotlight, as you were just talking about, the big power of shining the spotlight on developers who built something really cool.

00:23:37.420 --> 00:23:41.280
