00:38:10.480 --> 00:38:13.940
But Matt, I want to let you weigh in on the two ideas or two points.

00:38:13.940 --> 00:38:14.660
Yeah, for sure.

00:38:14.660 --> 00:38:21.860
Well, the very first step, if someone wants to be a developer and developer relations, is to be really deep in your tech stack.

00:38:21.860 --> 00:38:26.480
I sometimes field questions from folks and they say, hey, I've been programming for a while.

00:38:26.480 --> 00:38:27.620
I want to get out of programming.

00:38:27.620 --> 00:38:29.240
Can I go into evangelism?

00:38:29.240 --> 00:38:33.380
And I say, actually, that's the opposite thing you want to do.

00:38:33.820 --> 00:38:40.780
Because when you're a heads down developer like I was for a long time, you have time to focus on really hard problems.

00:38:40.780 --> 00:38:50.100
And when you're an evangelist or an advocate, typically you have a lot more demands on your time that cause you to kind of have two hours here, maybe three hours there.

00:38:50.100 --> 00:38:52.560
Or you're in an airport trying to debug some code.

00:38:52.780 --> 00:39:02.800
So you really have to be deep in your tech stack and just love coding because there's so many other distractions that are there for you when you're traveling or you're writing blog posts, things like that.

00:39:02.800 --> 00:39:08.500
I think that Cecil is spot on in that people have different strengths and you should play to your strengths.

00:39:08.980 --> 00:39:16.100
So if you're really deep in your tech stack and you really love writing, just do that and focus on that and become a better writer every day.

00:39:16.100 --> 00:39:19.440
If you like the public speaking side, that's awesome.

00:39:19.440 --> 00:39:24.920
I mean, that tends to be the most visible because when people go to conferences, they're like, oh, this person is a really great public speaker.

00:39:24.920 --> 00:39:26.960
Not everyone has to fall into that boat.

00:39:27.520 --> 00:39:31.280
But I just think that, you know, you kind of have to figure out, like, what am I really good at?

00:39:31.280 --> 00:39:34.000
You dabble in a bunch of things and say, what are my strengths?

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:44.540
And then it's the combination of being deep in your tech stack and with something else that helps other developers learn, which is really where the power comes in.

00:39:44.540 --> 00:39:46.960
And I actually completely disagree with Paul.

00:39:46.960 --> 00:39:51.540
I think there actually are significant metrics for measuring ROI to companies.

00:39:52.040 --> 00:40:04.400
And you can tie your own performance to those metrics and be confident that the work that you are doing, regardless of whether it's public speaking or blogging or open source work, is actually really, really valuable to your company.

00:40:04.400 --> 00:40:04.780
Nice.

