We're coming back to that then.

00:40:05.780 --> 00:40:21.280
So one thing I do want to throw out there, though, one of the shifts that I had when I switched into from being a regular developer to doing training, and I think would be quite similar to developer evangelist, is when you're a regular developer, if you find one way to solve a problem,

00:40:21.920 --> 00:40:22.280
you're good.

00:40:22.280 --> 00:40:23.160
You solve your problem.

00:40:23.160 --> 00:40:24.320
You check in the code.

00:40:24.320 --> 00:40:25.380
You go on to the next thing.

00:40:25.380 --> 00:40:35.000
But if you are representing a tech stack or a product or you're teaching somebody about one of those, like in the course of training, you need to know, oh, there's actually four ways to do this.

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:37.020
These are the tradeoffs between them.

00:40:37.020 --> 00:40:39.620
This is the situation when you use this one versus that one.

00:40:39.620 --> 00:40:45.380
And that's just like a different level of digging into learning a technology and a curiosity about it.

00:40:45.380 --> 00:40:48.820
It's not enough to, like, make it work one way.

00:40:48.900 --> 00:40:52.420
You have to understand sort of the tradeoffs in a little bit deeper.

00:40:52.420 --> 00:40:53.260
What do you guys think?

