00:44:44.200 --> 00:44:45.460
What are the metrics?

00:44:45.460 --> 00:44:47.080
Yeah, like how do you measure this?

00:44:47.080 --> 00:44:50.380
Like what looks like success for Twilio, and how do you know if you're doing it?

00:44:50.380 --> 00:44:58.120
Yeah, so it's very important to tie the developer relations program to the company strategy and the overall metrics that a business has.

00:44:58.340 --> 00:45:03.000
And so Twilio's mission is to help developers build the future of communications.

00:45:03.000 --> 00:45:09.820
And we want every developer in the world to have Twilio in their tool belt so that if they need to add two-factor authentication to an application,

00:45:09.820 --> 00:45:16.620
or they want to build a custom call center for their company, that they say, oh, I can do that with Twilio.

00:45:16.680 --> 00:45:24.840
And so for us, like a lot of the ROI calculated, return on investment calculations are around how many developers are actually using Twilio.

00:45:24.840 --> 00:45:32.520
Like we have usage metrics, and we can very clearly tie like which blog posts are actually driving the most usage of various products.

00:45:32.520 --> 00:45:47.340
You know, I think that's an interesting point because you, in particular with Full Stack Python, are really good at looking at analytics and sort of fine-tuning the web pages and the web stories to really resonate best,

00:45:47.340 --> 00:45:49.060
and then even changing them a little bit.

00:45:49.060 --> 00:45:50.600
So it can be done, right?

00:45:50.600 --> 00:45:51.720
It absolutely can be done.

00:45:51.720 --> 00:45:54.220
And, you know, I said I kind of disagree with Paul.

00:45:54.220 --> 00:45:59.920
I also want to agree with him in a way that you have to do what's best for developers.

00:46:00.500 --> 00:46:04.100
If you let the metrics drive you completely, you're going to do it wrong.

00:46:04.100 --> 00:46:06.800
Like you have to be a developer.

00:46:06.800 --> 00:46:11.080
You have to be a part of your community and know what's right and what's wrong.

00:46:11.080 --> 00:46:16.680
And then you kind of have like these internal metrics that show that what you're doing is valuable.

00:46:16.680 --> 00:46:19.100
So there's almost a little bit of two sides to it.

00:46:19.100 --> 00:46:20.520
You have I'm a developer.

00:46:20.520 --> 00:46:23.640
I know what's right for my community, and you really want that to happen.

00:46:23.640 --> 00:46:25.220
That's your ideal.

00:46:25.220 --> 00:46:26.300
That's what you drive towards.

00:46:26.300 --> 00:46:34.680
But then you also have the metrics that allow you to justify the expansion of the continued existence and the expansion of a developer relations program.

00:46:34.680 --> 00:46:37.200
So you can continue to help more and more developers over time.

00:46:37.200 --> 00:46:37.500
Yeah.

00:46:37.500 --> 00:46:38.060
Paul?

00:46:38.060 --> 00:46:39.120
Yeah, I'll jump in on that.

00:46:39.120 --> 00:46:40.200
That sounds great.

00:46:40.200 --> 00:46:42.740
I can promise you I'll be following up with you about that.

00:46:43.500 --> 00:46:48.960
In particular, on the macro side, the team as a whole's impact on the company.

00:46:48.960 --> 00:46:56.000
I was talking more in the context of a fairly self-directed job activity.

00:46:56.000 --> 00:46:58.880
Should I do this or that task?

00:46:59.480 --> 00:47:10.520
And it's pretty hard to get the granularity at the micro level versus the macro level of this blog post led to that impact.

00:47:10.520 --> 00:47:15.380
And maybe your context allows you to because of both ends of the equation on that.

00:47:15.380 --> 00:47:17.560
Or even giving a conference talk.

00:47:17.560 --> 00:47:24.940
We debate this endlessly about how to concoct measurements, how many people show up, what were the follow-ups afterwards.

00:47:25.580 --> 00:47:35.900
So certain activities, if metrics are introduced, create perverse incentives that poison the mission of developer relations.

00:47:35.900 --> 00:47:38.240
That's the worry that I have.

00:47:38.240 --> 00:47:39.120
Yeah.

00:47:39.120 --> 00:47:43.440
I think a lot, too, comes down to the company's strategy and business model.

00:47:43.440 --> 00:47:49.720
I actually would never be a developer evangelist or work in developer relations for a company that has a free API.

00:47:49.720 --> 00:47:54.600
Because if it's not worth paying for, then it could immediately be disbanded.

00:47:54.700 --> 00:47:56.100
Like Netflix had an API.

00:47:56.100 --> 00:47:56.580
Gone.

00:47:56.580 --> 00:48:07.060
So to me, to be able to tie the company making money off of an API so that it continues to justify investment is actually what drives a successful relations program.

00:48:07.060 --> 00:48:12.120
Now, it's harder to do that when you're talking about a subscription model or a one-time purchase model.

00:48:12.120 --> 00:48:16.560
So I think a lot comes down to the company's strategy and business model.

00:48:16.560 --> 00:48:20.500
Dude, make a PyCon talk this year on this topic.

00:48:21.600 --> 00:48:23.280
I'm sure a lot of companies would be interested.

00:48:23.280 --> 00:48:26.100
Cecil, how do you guys measure success?

00:48:26.100 --> 00:48:27.740
How do you know if you're doing better?

00:48:27.740 --> 00:48:32.720
So this is a problem that we've had that we're continuously trying to iterate over and figure out.

00:48:32.720 --> 00:48:36.820
So just for context, my team is maybe about a year and a half old.

00:48:36.820 --> 00:48:41.100
We started, I want to say, April or so, 2017.

00:48:41.600 --> 00:48:45.720
So one of the things that we do is, so we have like this internal dashboard.

00:48:45.720 --> 00:48:50.820
But essentially, all we're really doing is just tracking to see, like we're doing click tracking for the most part.

00:48:50.820 --> 00:48:52.520
And that's one of the strategies that we use.

00:48:52.520 --> 00:48:58.620
Because it's kind of hard to say, hey, if I went to this conference and I gave this talk or you watched my video.

00:48:58.920 --> 00:49:05.280
You know, there's a person that watched the video, going to come and download Visual Studio, and you're going to sign up for an Azure account or whatever the case is.

00:49:05.280 --> 00:49:05.860
Right.

00:49:05.860 --> 00:49:10.080
So we do a little bit of click tracking to kind of flow people around and kind of follow them.

00:49:10.080 --> 00:49:15.220
But even with that, too, like those, that method is a little subjective, I suppose.

00:49:15.220 --> 00:49:18.040
Like how accurate is that exactly at the end of the day?

00:49:18.040 --> 00:49:26.760
And like, you know, like who's to say, you know, hey, this person didn't just like pass this thing around throughout all of this company and like take out my tracking link.

00:49:26.760 --> 00:49:26.940
Right.

00:49:26.940 --> 00:49:30.560
So like maybe there's more people that are coming in and they're just not clicking my link.

00:49:30.560 --> 00:49:33.400
But maybe I gave it to like you and you shared it around your company.

00:49:33.400 --> 00:49:35.740
Like I can't really track those people.

00:49:35.740 --> 00:49:40.480
And so I kind of look at it as a way to judge like relative change.

00:49:40.480 --> 00:49:45.500
I think that's a good way for us to look at those things versus like absolute numbers.

00:49:45.980 --> 00:49:51.820
Because if you look at it relatively, then you could say, OK, well, you know, maybe the strategy that we're taking is a good idea or a bad idea.

00:49:51.820 --> 00:49:55.100
Or, you know, maybe I don't know, like we change the background of the video.

00:49:55.100 --> 00:50:00.260
Like people don't really like to like we should change the background because our viewers just dropped off or something like that.

00:50:00.260 --> 00:50:08.600
But yeah, again, for us, it's just something that we're constantly trying to tweak and iterate over and just, you know, try different strategies to see what happens.

00:50:08.600 --> 00:50:08.840
Yeah.

00:50:08.840 --> 00:50:15.900
I think one thing that's important is that, you know, kind of like what Matt was alluding to a little bit, like we don't like our jobs aren't tight.

00:50:15.900 --> 00:50:16.620
And to metrics.

00:50:16.620 --> 00:50:19.060
So it's not like there's no competition here, right?

00:50:19.060 --> 00:50:19.880
There's no competition.

00:50:19.880 --> 00:50:22.060
There's no like, you know, in team fighting.

00:50:22.060 --> 00:50:23.540
Oh, I got to get more views than you do.

00:50:23.540 --> 00:50:27.840
You know, because again, like when you do that, like now your focus is different, right?

00:50:27.840 --> 00:50:36.220
Like you're looking at the wrong thing versus, you know, hey, I'm trying to be at the top of the leaderboard versus I just want to put out good content that people care about.

00:50:36.220 --> 00:50:37.100
Yeah, that makes a lot of sense.

00:50:37.100 --> 00:50:42.120
And you have so many different areas to measure like channel nine versus conferences versus other social.

00:50:42.120 --> 00:50:44.240
There's it's hard to know the relative value.

00:50:44.240 --> 00:50:44.880
I'm sure.

00:50:44.880 --> 00:50:45.200
Yeah.

